Table 3.5 lists the OAuth values that SHOUD be sent to the server:

Parameter

ê‡ñæ

Example

oauth_consumer_key

The public consumer key for the requester.

"imsglobal"

oauth_signature_method

The type of encryption used

"HMAC-SHA1"

oauth_timestamp

The timestamp of the message, unix long milliseconds from 1st Jan 1970.

"1487345558"

oauth_nonce

Number to use once - used to avoid replay attacks, and should be unique per request. Servers should store the nonces for 90 minutes to ensure that they are not reused.

"1965da178f762237a8506e9d51b0398b4"

oauth_version

The version of OAuth to use.

"1.0"

oauth_signature

The signature of the request itself (without the extra OAuth parameters) encrypted using the oauth_consumer_secret.

"z47QdbCsasZP+5ZXelvc2b9xQeU="

oauth_body_hash

This is computed using a SHA-1 hash of the body content. It is required for all HTTP PUT requests and must not be present for HTTP GET requests.

"v%2BxFnmDLwo%3D"

oauth_callback

Not Used - but may be required by implementing library.

"about:blank"
